---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Waybar from '../components/Waybar.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import BackToHome from '../components/BackToHome.astro';
import WindowChrome from '../components/WindowChrome.astro';
import VimStatusline from '../components/VimStatusline.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;


const lastUpdated = 'June 22, 2026';
---

<Layout title="How I use AI — Nirmal">
  <Waybar />

  <main id="main-content">
  <article class="ai-page grid-bg">
    <div class="ai-inner">
      <header class="ai-header">
        <div class="back-home-row"><BackToHome /></div>
        <h1 class="ai-h1">How I use AI</h1>
        <p class="ai-updated">Last updated: <span class="lime">{lastUpdated}</span></p>
      </header>

      <div class="ai-window vim-window">
        <WindowChrome title="how-i-use-ai.md" activeTitle="[+]" icon="UTF-8">
          <div class="ai-window-body vim-window-body">
            <div class="ai-body">
              <p>
              This page is a work in progress and will (hopefully) see regular updates, and it should be. I'm still 
              figuring out how AI fits into my daily life and where it is genuinely good for design, and where it is not.
              Treat this page as a record of where I've fgotten to so far and not as a fixed position.
              </p>

              <h2>Do I need a human designer? AI can make nice websites now.</h2>
              <p>
                Yeah! In 2026, most LLMs I've tried are really good at producing good looking websites. I vibe coded a wedding website for myself and 
                it looked fine! Do the sites all look just a bit similar? I'll leave that to you. So why should someone still employ a human designer? What do I 
                bring to the table that Gemini cannot? What are my thoughts on AI? Am I stuck in the past? Head strong? Rowing against the tide?
                
                Eh, no. I use AI where it helps. I design for humans (until the agentic web becomes a reality and we start designing for agents to have positive life-changing experiences) 
                My default answer is to keep my work grounded in real experiences of real people. AI is useful for moving faster and 
                for automating mundane work, but it's easy to let it sand the judgement out of a project: to accept a plausible 
                hypothesis instead of digging for an actual finding. I strive to keep a human in the loop wherever decisions are being made,
                to undestand research, what needs building, and what shouldn't be built.
              </p>
              <p>
                However, I'm not against designing for AI or a blanket "Keep AI away from the interface" rule. If there's a chance 
                to design useful AI tools, designing that interaction well is an important part of the job - this is craft and not compromise, 
                and nor will it be treated as one. My work on the chatbot in the Counselling Companions project is a demonstration of this commitment.
              </p>

              <h2>Restraint</h2>
              <p>
              I believe that the use of AI in interfaces has to come with clear guardrails and clear communication. Not 
              just for my peace of mind, but for improved adoption too. For my MSc thesis, I followed the Responsible Research and Innovation
              principles and mapped out sensitive data to understand what (and what couldn't) be handed over to AI. This helped place 
              key guardrails and build informed consent into the product from the ground up, also ensuring that a human reviewed 
              and approved any AI approved material before it could go onto the client record. This lesson has stayed, and I still think 
              that AI should feel like a tool held in the user's hand, and not an agent acting on its own. A lot of good design 
              is deciding where it belongs. 
                <em>(See: <a href={`${base}projects/counselling-companions`}>Crafting Counselling Companions</a>.)</em>
              </p>

              <h2>So how do you use AI?</h2>
              <p>
                I'm less precious about AI in the parts of the work where it speeds me up without making decisions for
                me.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong>Research.</strong> I use AI to help process and synthesise: transcript and anonymise, cluster codes, surface patterns across
                transcripts, draft first-pass analyses. I treat its output as a draft to verify against the raw
                data, never as the finding itself. I would like for the thinking to stay mine while the typing gets faster.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong>Tracking and planning.</strong> I lean on AI to keep projects organised — producing interactive HTML
                gantt chartgs turning messy notes into structure, keeping track of decisions and open threads: 
                so more of my attention goes into designing and less to the admin around it.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong>Building.</strong> This is where it's changed my work most. I use Claude skills and artifacts
                to scaffold, prototype, and generate live sites for usability testing, allowing me to test ideas in fairly high fidelity without
                having to invest hours into realistic Figma prototypes or trying to explain interactivity to testers while using 
                a static mockup with two buttons which have hover states. Speed only helps if the output stays true to the design system. I make 
                it a point to export design tokens off Figma and to store it in tool memory to generate realistic renders of concepts: the design 
                system keeps me consistent while the AI makes my processes quicker. 

                I <em><b>never treat AI models as stand-in users</b></em> as I understand how LLMs fundamentally work: they're great at finding the next word to from
                coherent sentences, but aren't human (no matter how many people I know talk to Chat GPT like it's their best friend) and cannot be trusted to
                understand human interactions or how site designs and layouts might be failing.
              </p>

              <h2>TL;DR</h2>
              <p>
              I'm trying to use AI as what it is - a tool. It's not a user, it's not a solution to all the world's problems (just yet). Humans 
              are still answerable for end results, and I only use it where it actually makes the work better. Do I have a subscription? Sure, I use
              Claude Pro and I experiment with local models in my free time, but this is all experimentation and will not affect work, unless I'm 
              happy with the results of any experiments while staying true to my fundamental beliefs around use of the technology. As my understanding shifts,
              so will this page.
                page.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <VimStatusline filename="how-i-use-ai.md" />
        </WindowChrome>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .ai-page {
    padding: 4rem 3rem;
  }

  .ai-inner {
    max-width: 880px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .ai-header {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }

  .back-home-row {
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .ai-h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4rem);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
    line-height: 1;
    color: var(--lime);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .ai-updated {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--dim);
  }

  .ai-updated .lime {
    color: var(--lime);
  }

  .ai-window {
    padding-bottom: 3rem;
    scroll-snap-align: center;
  }

  .ai-window :global(.window) {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    height: calc(100vh - var(--bar-h) - 2rem);
    position: sticky;
    top: calc(var(--bar-h) + 1rem);
  }

  .ai-window-body {
    background: var(--bg1);
    padding: 2rem 1.75rem;
    overflow-y: hidden;
    flex: 1;
    min-height: 0;
  }

  .ai-body {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    color: var(--sub);
    line-height: 1.75;
    animation: ai-fade-in 0.18s ease-out;
  }

  @keyframes ai-fade-in {
    from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(4px); }
    to { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
  }

  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .ai-body { animation: none; }
  }

  .ai-body p {
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    max-width: 68ch;
  }

  .ai-body h2 {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    color: var(--text);
    margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem;
  }

  .ai-body h2:first-child {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .ai-body strong {
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .ai-body em {
    color: var(--dim);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .ai-body a {
    color: var(--lime);
    text-decoration: none;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(158,255,87,0.35);
  }

  .ai-body a:hover {
    border-bottom-color: var(--lime);
  }

  @media (max-width: 860px) {
    .ai-page { padding: 2.5rem 1.25rem; }
    .ai-window { height: auto !important; }
    .ai-window :global(.window) { height: auto; position: static; }
    .ai-window-body { overflow-y: visible; flex: none; }
  }

  @media (max-width: 480px) {
    .ai-page { padding: 1.75rem 0.75rem; }
  }
</style>

<script>
  import { initVimWindow } from '../lib/vim-window';
  initVimWindow();
</script>
